data.content:
Here's the complete migration. Your code has three `Thread.Abort`-dependent patterns that don't exist in modern .NET:

| Pattern | Location | Problem in .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | `btnExport_Click` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | `true` (endResponse) called `Thread.Abort` internally |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | Never thrown — dead code that hides bugs |

## Migrated ASP.NET Core Controller

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // Export: Return a FileResult — the framework handles headers/streaming.
    // No Response.Clear(), .Write(), or .End() needed.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    // Redirect: Return IActionResult instead of calling Response.Redirect.
    // No Thread.Abort, no ThreadAbortException, no swallowing.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key changes explained

**1. `Response.End()` → just return**
ASP.NET Core has no `Response.End()`. Action methods return `IActionResult`; the framework writes the response. For file downloads, `File()` sets `Content-Type`, `Content-Disposition`, and streams the body — replacing `Clear()`, `AddHeader()`, `Write()`, and `End()` in one call.

**2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` → `return Redirect(url)`**
The `true` parameter existed solely to abort the thread and stop further execution. In ASP.NET Core, `return Redirect(...)` exits the method naturally — no abort needed.

**3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → remove entirely**
This block only existed because `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw `ThreadAbortException` as a side effect. With `return Redirect(...)`, no exception is thrown. Removing this catch also eliminates a subtle bug: the old code swallowed `ThreadAbortException` from `Response.Redirect("/success", true)`, which meant if `ProcessRequest()` succeeded, the redirect still triggered an exception caught by the (now-removed) catch block.

## Common pitfalls during this migration

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| Writing to `Response.Body` then calling `return Redirect()` | Can't redirect after writing — you'll get `InvalidOperationException`. Choose one response type. |
| Forgetting `?.` on `User.Identity` | In ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` can be `null` if no auth middleware runs. The old code assumed it was always non-null. |
| Keeping `catch (ThreadAbortException)` as dead code | It will never fire in .NET 8 (`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`). Worse, it silently masks the fact that your control flow has changed. |
| Using `HttpResponse.Redirect()` instead of returning `IActionResult` | Calling `Response.Redirect()` directly in ASP.NET Core **does not** stop method execution — code after it continues to run, potentially writing a second response. Always use `return Redirect()`. |
